    <p>Most African-Grey-versus-cockatoo articles are written by people selling neither bird. We're Mark and Teri Benjamin, and we've hand-raised African Greys here at C.A.Gs since 2014 — weighing chicks at 6 a.m. and fielding the "should I get a cockatoo instead?" question year-round. When we describe a Grey trait on this page it comes from our own nursery; when we describe a cockatoo, it comes from the owners, rescues and avian vets we've spent a decade comparing notes with.</p>
    <p>That honesty runs both ways. We'll tell you plainly that a cockatoo out-cuddles any Grey, and that a Goffin's may out-think one at raw problem-solving — because a comparison that only flatters the bird we sell is an ad, not a comparison. What we won't do is repeat the internet's confident folklore about either species without checking it against real birds first.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The C.A.Gs Philosophy: Health-Documentation ROI</h3>
    <p>For any parrot the purchase is the cheap part; the real expense is the four to eight decades that follow. So we load the unglamorous paperwork up front to guard those years: PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus PCR screening, a DNA sexing certificate, an avian vet's health certificate, a hatch record with closed band, and the CITES Appendix I documents establishing that your Grey was bred in captivity here in the States. Whichever bird wins you over, our <a href="/african-grey-parrot-health-guarantee/">health guarantee page</a> puts that whole stack in writing.</p>
