  <!-- S8 AFRICAN GREY DEEP DIVE -->
  <section id="grey">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Makes the African Grey the Talking Champion?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img portrait" src="/bery-congo-african-grey-female-1-year.webp" width="760" height="760" alt="A hand-raised African Grey taking a seed from its keeper's hand, showing the silver-grey head, light eye and solid black beak" loading="lazy">
    <p>The African Grey is the parrot that made "talking bird" mean something. Silver-grey body, dark beak, a bright red tail on the Congo — and behind that plain plumage, the vocabulary and contextual reasoning that put the species in psychology textbooks. Against a cockatoo, the Grey's whole case is the mind: it talks, it problem-solves, and it entertains itself for stretches instead of demanding to be worn like a scarf. If you've searched "are African Greys good pets" or "best talking parrot," this is the from-the-nursery answer. You can meet the chicks weaning now on our <a href="/congo-african-grey-for-sale/">available Congo Grey</a> and <a href="/timneh-african-grey-for-sale/">Timneh Grey</a> pages.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Big Is an African Grey, and How Long Does It Live?</h3>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-size-weight-vs-cockatoo.webp" srcset="/african-grey-size-weight-vs-cockatoo-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-size-weight-vs-cockatoo.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Infographic showing African Grey size of 12 to 14 inches and 400 to 600 grams against cockatoo species ranging from the small Goffin's to the large Moluccan" loading="lazy">
    <p>A healthy Congo African Grey weighs 400–600 grams at 12–14 inches beak to tail; the Timneh runs smaller. That places the Grey below most cockatoos on the size chart — a Goffin's is close, but an Umbrella or Moluccan dwarfs it. Smaller bird, smaller cage footprint, and a bite that stops well short of a big cockatoo's. Lifespan is the sobering match: 40–60 years with proper diet, UV-B light and avian-vet care, which is squarely in cockatoo territory. Either bird is a decades-long promise.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">What Is an African Grey's Temperament Like?</h3>
    <p>Watchful. A Grey clocks everything — new shoes, moved furniture, which mug you grabbed — and that vigilance is both the appeal and the maintenance bill: a bird that notices everything needs a home worth noticing. Where a cockatoo wears its heart on its crest and demands contact, the Grey is more reserved and observational, happier supervising you from a perch than riding your chest. It bonds hard, but on its own terms.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Is an African Grey Right for an Apartment?</h4>
    <p>Usually yes — and here the Grey pulls decisively ahead of a cockatoo. Greys aren't screamers by disposition; their signature sounds are whistles, talking and appliance mimicry, with real but predictable dawn and dusk peaks. A cockatoo's contact scream, by contrast, is an eviction risk through shared walls. Expect your microwave beep back at you forever, but expect it at a volume thin walls survive. A Moluccan they would not.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">How Does an African Grey Bond?</h4>
    <p>Deeply, and often with one favorite person, after weeks of quietly deciding who's trustworthy — a pattern owners on <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/parrots/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">r/parrots ↗</a> describe exactly as we see it in the nursery. It's a steadier devotion than a cockatoo's full-body clinginess: a Grey wants to be in the room with its person, not welded to them. If you want a bird that interacts more than it clings, that's the Grey. If the cuddle is the whole point, the cockatoo section below is about to sound good.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">What Grey Owners Notice in Week One</h5>
    <p>A new Grey that looks "boring" in its first week is anything but — it's quietly sizing you up. It'll perch low, observe far more than it acts, and wait until you've left the room to eat. By the second week that assessment wraps up and the character starts showing through. Our line to every family: a hushed opening week is the mark of a well-adjusted Grey, not a disappointed one.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: Maxy's first words</h6>
    <p>Maxy — the Grey you'll see in our homepage video — began exactly the way the species tends to, by seizing on the single handiest word around him. He picked up calling "Teri," and the moment that paid off, "bye bye" and "come here please" arrived close behind. That's not idle mimicry; it's vocabulary aimed at an outcome. We've yet to meet a cockatoo that does it, and it's the entire reason the Grey takes the talking round.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Which Health Risks Do We Screen African Greys For?</h3>
    <p>Two conditions deserve a spot on every Grey buyer's radar — and, tellingly, both trouble cockatoos as well. The first is hypocalcemia: Greys handle calcium unlike most parrots, and the veterinary literature summarized at <a href="https://lafeber.com/vet/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lafeber's avian resources ↗</a> flags low blood calcium as a well-documented grey-specific hazard, headed off with the right diet and UV-B light — the reason full-spectrum lighting appears in our care notes from day one. The second is feather-destructive behavior, where an unstimulated Grey grooms itself raw, precisely as a bored cockatoo will. Neither outcome is fated, and both are why we screen our buyers as closely as they screen us.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Hypocalcemia &amp; Feather-Destructive Behavior, Plainly</h4>
    <p>Low calcium presents as weakness or, at its worst, seizures — and it's largely headed off with a pellet-forward diet, calcium-rich fresh foods and UV-B exposure. Feather-destructive behavior is really an enrichment failure wearing a medical mask: a Grey with genuine work to do seldom shreds its plumage, and a cockatoo is no different. The owner guides at <a href="https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/african-grey-parrots-general" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VCA Animal Hospitals ↗</a> walk through both in plain terms, and every buyer of ours receives our precise diet and lighting plan on paper.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">What Our PBFD and Polyomavirus Screen Catches</h5>
    <p>Beak and Feather Disease and Avian Polyomavirus are the pair of viruses that turn a "cheap parrot" into an expensive mistake, and they strike cockatoos just as readily as Greys. We run a PCR panel on every Grey for both — an actual laboratory result on the individual bird, not a reassuring sentence on a listing. It's also why we urge buyers to leave any seller, of either species, who can't hand over the same lab work.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: World Parrot Trust species profile</h6>
    <p>The species-level claims above line up with the <a href="https://www.parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">World Parrot Trust profile of <em>Psittacus erithacus</em> ↗</a> — a group whose trade research helped break the wild-capture habit that once hung over Greys and cockatoos alike.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S9 COCKATOO FAMILY DEEP DIVE -->
  <section id="cockatoo">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Are Cockatoos Really Like to Live With?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/cockatoo-family-traits-infographic.webp" srcset="/cockatoo-family-traits-infographic-760.webp 760w, /cockatoo-family-traits-infographic.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Infographic of the pet cockatoo species — Umbrella, Moluccan, Goffin's, Galah and Citron — with a one-word trait for each beside the African Grey" loading="lazy">
    <p>Cockatoos are the white (and pink, and salmon) crested parrots of Australasia, and living with one is a different proposition from living with a Grey. Where the Grey leads with its mind, a cockatoo leads with its heart — enormous affection, enormous volume, and an emotional dependency that makes them the most rewarding and most surrendered parrots in the trade at the same time. The pet-kept species range from the pocket-sized Goffin's to the enormous Moluccan, and we'll take each by name further down. First, the traits they share.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why Are Cockatoos Called "Velcro Birds"?</h3>
    <p>Because they attach. A well-bonded cockatoo wants physical contact for hours — on your shoulder, under your chin, tucked into your neck — in a way no African Grey ever asks for. For the right owner that constant cuddling is the entire appeal, the thing a reserved Grey will never give. The catch is that the need is not optional: a cockatoo denied contact doesn't become independent, it becomes distressed. Buy the cuddle and you buy the obligation behind it.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Loud and Demanding Is a Cockatoo?</h3>
    <p>Loud enough to reset the whole comparison. A cockatoo's contact call is instinctive and can run for long stretches, and the largest species produce some of the loudest sounds in aviculture — a Moluccan's scream is measured near the top of the companion-bird chart. Forum owners are blunt about the workload: on <a href="https://forums.avianavenue.com/index.php?threads/grey-or-cockatoo.148234/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Avian Avenue ↗</a> a keeper of both put cockatoos at "seven times more work" than a Grey. That gap is the single biggest reason we point apartment buyers toward the Grey.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Why Do So Many Cockatoos Get Surrendered?</h4>
    <p>The volume and the neediness together. When a cockatoo's emotional needs outrun what a household can give, the results are screaming, biting and self-mutilation — and owners who weren't ready describe, in the words of one <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/parrots/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">r/parrots ↗</a> thread, "100% insanity for years." Rescues fill with cockatoos for exactly this reason. Greys are surrendered too, usually from boredom-driven plucking, but the cockatoo rehoming pipeline is in a category of its own. Going in clear-eyed is the whole job.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Are Cockatoos Smart? The Contrafreeloading Question</h3>
    <p>Very — just in a different direction than the Grey. Cockatoos are elite problem-solvers; Goffin's have been filmed spontaneously making and using tools, a feat that rivals the Grey's language résumé. That intelligence is also why an under-stimulated cockatoo self-destructs: a mind built for foraging and manipulation, with nothing to work on, turns on its own feathers.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Enrichment Prevents Plucking — in Both Species</h4>
    <p>The research backs the practical advice. In Dr. Irene Pepperberg's lab, umbrella cockatoos and African greys both showed "contrafreeloading" — choosing to work for food that was also freely available — because the working itself is enriching. The takeaway for a buyer is identical for both birds: a parrot with real foraging work rarely plucks, and a bored one often does. Neither species is a cage ornament; both are full-time enrichment projects.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">Citation: Dr. Irene Pepperberg's contrafreeloading study</h5>
    <p>Figures here come from the <a href="https://lafeber.com/pet-birds/inside-dr-pepperbergs-lab-greys-vs-umbrella-cockatoos-who-likes-to-work-for-their-food/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lafeber write-up of Carroll &amp; Pepperberg's umbrella-cockatoo study ↗</a>, which found wide individual variation (one cockatoo contrafreeloaded 71% of the time, another just 4%) and no significant overall difference between greys and cockatoos.</p>
  </section>

