  <!-- S11 TALKING -->
  <section id="talking">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Which Talks Better — an African Grey or a Cockatoo?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-talking-ability.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-talking-ability-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-cockatoo-talking-ability.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Talking-ability infographic showing the African Grey at 200 to 1,000-plus words with clear speech against the cockatoo's handful of words" loading="lazy">
    <p>Here's the honest version, and it's not close: <strong>the African Grey wins talking outright.</strong> Greys command vocabularies of 200 to 1,000-plus words with near-human clarity and — the part that matters — a documented capacity to use words in context. Cockatoos can pick up a few words and phrases, but speech isn't their headline talent. If a bird that genuinely converses is the goal, this chapter ends the comparison.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Many Words — and Does the Bird Understand Them?</h3>
    <p>Vocabulary is only half the Grey's edge; comprehension is the other half. Alex, the African Grey studied for thirty years by Dr. Irene Pepperberg, could label colors, shapes and quantities and answer novel questions — evidence of contextual language, not just parroting. That's the ceiling no cockatoo approaches. Our <a href="/blog/african-grey-parrot-talking-ability/">African Grey talking-ability guide</a> walks through what to realistically expect month by month.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Can Cockatoos Talk at All?</h4>
    <p>Yes — modestly. Most pet cockatoos learn a handful of words, a whistle or two, and the occasional startling phrase, usually in a gravelly, less articulate voice than a Grey's. But nobody buys a cockatoo for its vocabulary; they buy it for the dancing, the affection and the sheer personality. Judging a cockatoo on talking is like judging a Grey on cuddling — you're grading the wrong subject.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">Why Individual Birds Beat the Averages</h5>
    <p>Every rule here has exceptions in feathers. We've weaned quiet Greys that whistle more than they talk, and there are famously chatty cockatoos on the internet. Averages tell you which way to bet, not what your specific bird will do. If talking is non-negotiable, the Grey is the safe bet — but "guaranteed talker" is a promise no honest breeder of either species makes.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: Alex the Grey &amp; Britannica</h6>
    <p>The species-level claim rests on the record: <a href="https://www.britannica.com/animal/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Encyclopaedia Britannica ↗</a> calls the African Grey "unsurpassed as a talker," and Pepperberg's three decades with Alex remain the benchmark study of parrot cognition.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S12 NOISE & APARTMENT -->
  <section id="noise">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Which Is Louder — and Can It Live in an Apartment?</h2>
    <p>Noise ends more parrot placements than price ever does, so apartment dwellers should read this section twice. <strong>Quick answer: the African Grey is far quieter, and the only realistically apartment-compatible bird of the two.</strong></p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-noise-meter.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-noise-meter-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-cockatoo-noise-meter.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Noise-meter infographic placing the African Grey in the moderate band and the Moluccan cockatoo in the very-loud red zone among the loudest companion birds" loading="lazy">
    <p>A Grey sits in the moderate band of the parrot noise chart — whistles, talking, appliance mimicry, and predictable dawn and dusk vocal sessions. Cockatoos occupy the top of that chart, and a Moluccan's contact scream is measured among the loudest sounds any companion animal makes, built in the wild to carry over a mile. Through shared apartment walls, that gap isn't a nuance; it's a lease.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Which Cockatoo Is Quietest?</h3>
    <p>If your heart is set on a cockatoo but you have neighbors, the Galah is the least loud of the common species — smaller, calmer and easier on the walls than an Umbrella or Moluccan. It is still louder than a Grey. There is no silent cockatoo; there is only "less catastrophic," and the Galah is where that road ends.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S13 DANDER & ALLERGIES -->
  <section id="dander">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Powder Down, Dander &amp; Allergies — the Honest Version</h2>
    <p><strong>Neither bird is allergy-safe.</strong> This is where we part ways with pages that sell the Grey as the "clean" option: African Greys and cockatoos are both powder-down species, producing a fine feather dust that settles on shelves and, more importantly, stays airborne.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-dander-allergy.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-dander-allergy-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-cockatoo-dander-allergy.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Infographic showing both the African Grey and the cockatoo as powder-down birds that produce feather dander, with the cockatoo producing more" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Is One Bird Safer for Allergy Sufferers?</h3>
    <p>Cockatoos produce even more powder than Greys — enough that owners run air purifiers as standard kit — but that's a difference of degree, not kind. Per <a href="https://www.parrots.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">avian welfare educators ↗</a>, parrots from Africa (greys) and Australasia (cockatoos) are the dustiest groups; South American parrots produce less. So "get a Grey instead" is not an allergy solution.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">What Reduces Feather Dust in Either Species</h4>
    <p>Regular bathing or misting keeps powder down, a HEPA air purifier near the cage clears what goes airborne, and a wipeable surface routine handles the rest. These are the same measures for both birds — the cockatoo just needs them turned up.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Bottom Line for Allergy-Prone Homes</h5>
    <p>If bird allergies or asthma run in your household, spend an afternoon around adult birds of either species before you commit, and budget for an air purifier regardless. We'd rather lose a sale than place any bird in a home that can't breathe with it.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: hypersensitivity pneumonitis from a grey parrot</h6>
    <p>This isn't hypothetical: a peer-reviewed case in the <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9381342/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">U.S. National Library of Medicine ↗</a> documents hypersensitivity pneumonitis in an owner, confirmed against their African Grey's feathers. Powder-down dander is a real respiratory variable for both species.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S14 BITE FORCE & SAFETY -->
  <section id="safety">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Bite Force &amp; Home Safety</h2>
    <p>Late-stage buyers ask the question nobody likes to say out loud: how much damage can it do? <strong>Both birds can bite hard; the cockatoo can bite much harder.</strong></p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-bite-force-safety.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-bite-force-safety-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-cockatoo-bite-force-safety.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Bite-force safety infographic comparing an African Grey's 61 to 96 newton bite with the much stronger bite of a large cockatoo" loading="lazy">
    <p>An African Grey bites at roughly 61–96 newtons — about 70–220 PSI, enough to break skin and, memorably, to snap a wooden popsicle stick. A large cockatoo generates substantially more, with a beak built to crack hard nuts and, if it decides to, a finger. Neither bird bites without reason, and both telegraph it, but the margin for error around children is plainly wider with a Grey.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Popsicle-Stick Test</h3>
    <p>Here's the tangible version: a Grey's worst bite lands near the force of snapping a sturdy popsicle stick — it hurts and can draw blood, but it heals. A big cockatoo's bite is in a different tier and warrants genuine supervision around small children and other pets. Respect the beak, read the body language, and neither bird ever has to bite at all.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S15 SCORECARD — Gemini scorecard image + real data table kept in DOM for AIO -->
  <section id="scorecard">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Decision Scorecard: African Grey vs Cockatoo Across 7 Traits</h2>
    <p>Landed here from a "which parrot is better, African Grey or cockatoo" search? Here's the verdict as numbers. Every score below is our own on a 0-to-10 scale, drawn from raising Greys and trading notes with cockatoo keepers and rescues — judgment calls rather than lab readouts — and we've kept them honest about the columns where the cockatoo comes out ahead.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-decision-scorecard.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-decision-scorecard-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-cockatoo-decision-scorecard.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Decision scorecard infographic rating the African Grey and cockatoo from zero to ten on talking, independence, cuddliness, quietness, beginner fit, low dander and apartment fit" loading="lazy">
    <div class="tbl-wrap plain"><table class="score-tbl">
      <thead><tr><th>Trait</th><th>African Grey</th><th>Cockatoo</th><th>Our note</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>{scores.map((s) => (<tr><td class="sc-trait" data-label="Trait">{s.trait}</td><td class="sc" data-label="African Grey">{s.c}</td><td class="sc" data-label="Cockatoo">{s.t}</td><td class="sc-note" data-label="Our note">{s.note}</td></tr>))}</tbody>
    </table></div>
    <p>Read the pattern, not the totals: the Grey owns talking, independence, quiet and apartment fit; the cockatoo owns cuddliness outright. Neither column is a bad bird — you're choosing between a companion that converses and one that clings.</p>
  </section>

