  <!-- S16 WHICH FITS YOUR HOUSEHOLD -->
  <section id="household">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Which Parrot Fits Your Household?</h2>
    <p>Scores are useful; households are specific. Whether you're after the best parrot for apartment life, a bird that fits a busy family, or a companion for a quiet retirement, the real match turns on who's home, how much noise you can absorb, and whether you'd sooner talk to your bird or hold it. Find your situation below — it's the very rundown we give over email.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/which-parrot-fits-you-flowchart.webp" srcset="/which-parrot-fits-you-flowchart-760.webp 760w, /which-parrot-fits-you-flowchart.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Flowchart matching households to the African Grey or a cockatoo based on work hours, desire to talk, and noise tolerance" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Match by Household</h3>
    <p>Five genuine household types, five straight answers — including the one where the honest reply is "perhaps hold off this year."</p>
    <div class="match-grid">
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">First-Time Bird Owner</h4><p>Lean African Grey, with eyes open. Neither species is a true beginner bird, but a Grey is more forgiving than a large cockatoo, whose volume and neediness overwhelm most first-timers and fill rescues. If a cockatoo is the dream, start with a smaller Galah and heavy research.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Family with Kids</h4><p>Lean African Grey, on bite force and noise. A big cockatoo's beak and volume are a lot for a house with young children, and its one-person intensity can leave the kids out. Either bird needs supervised distance from toddlers — this is a decades-long commitment, not a starter pet.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Apartment or Condo</h4><p>African Grey, clearly — the only one of the two thin walls reliably survive. If a cockatoo is non-negotiable, only a Galah is even in the conversation, and your neighbors still get a vote. Both birds need daily out-of-cage time regardless of square footage.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">You Want to Be Cuddled</h4><p>This is the cockatoo's household. If the dream is a bird that sits on you for hours and craves contact, no Grey will deliver it — choose the species by that honest want, then commit to the noise and neediness that ride along. A Galah or Umbrella, not a Grey.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Busy Professional</h4><p>Think hard, then think again — for either bird. A parrot alone ten hours a day is how plucking starts, and a lonely cockatoo unravels faster than a lonely Grey. If your schedule is genuinely full, this may be the year to wait rather than the year to buy.</p></div>
    </div>
    <p>Not settled even after all that? That's exactly our job — the form at the foot of this page lands straight with Mark and Teri, and "is it a Grey or a cockatoo for us" is one of our favorite messages to reply to.</p>
  </section>

