  <!-- S17 COST -->
  <section id="cost">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Does an African Grey Cost vs a Cockatoo?</h2>
    <p>Prices up front, since a page that hides them earns no trust: our documented African Greys run $1,700–$3,500 (Congo) and $1,500–$1,600 (Timneh), and a $200 deposit holds one. Cockatoos span roughly $1,000–$4,000 by species, Moluccans and Umbrellas at the top with Goffin's and Galahs lower down. The <a href="/african-grey-parrot-price/">price guide</a> carries our current per-bird pricing, refreshed as clutches wean.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-cost-breakdown.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-cost-breakdown-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-cockatoo-cost-breakdown.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Cost-breakdown infographic showing African Grey prices of 1,500 to 3,500 dollars and a first-year setup budget of roughly 825 to 2,000 dollars" loading="lazy">

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why the Sticker Price Is the Cheap Part</h3>
    <p>For either species the purchase price is a rounding error against the four to eight decades of food, vet visits, toys and caging still to come. The danger lurks at the bottom of both markets: those $800 "bargain" listings with no CITES papers, no sexing certificate and no vet check are the ones that generate the fraud complaints, and they top the list of ads buyers forward us to vet. A papered bird costs what it does because the paperwork represents genuine labor; a paperless one isn't a bargain, it's a wholly different — and riskier — purchase.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">What's Included in Our Grey's Price</h4>
    <p>Our price folds in the entire trust stack with nothing itemized on top: captive-bred CITES papers, a DNA sexing certificate, an avian veterinarian's health certificate, a hatch record with the closed band number, and PBFD plus Polyomavirus PCR results. The one extra you'll ever pay is transport — $185 to your airport or $350 to your door.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">First-Year Budget Beyond the Bird</h5>
    <p>Budget somewhere around $825 to $2,000 in the first year beyond the bird itself: a genuinely large cage ($300–$800, and a cockatoo wants the top of that range), starter perches and toys ($100–$300), that first wellness exam ($75–$200 — the <a href="https://www.aav.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Association of Avian Veterinarians ↗</a> lists certified avian vets by area), twelve months of good pellets ($200–$400), and rotating enrichment ($150–$300, more if a cockatoo is demolishing it). After year one, plan on roughly $375 to $1,350 annually.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: why we don't sell unweaned chicks</h6>
    <p>Cheaper unweaned chicks — Grey and cockatoo alike — are all over the internet. We won't sell one at any price: botched hand-feeding, from crop burns to aspiration, kills babies in unpracticed hands, and "wean it yourself and pocket the difference" is the single worst gamble in this hobby. Every bird we place has already been fully weaned, and that's built into what you pay.</p>
  </section>

