  <!-- S18 FIRST 30 DAYS -->
  <section id="first30">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Do the First 30 Days With a Grey Look Like?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img" src="/amie-congo-african-grey-handfed-baby-card.webp" width="640" height="480" alt="A fully hand-fed baby African Grey being raised at C.A.Gs before going home" loading="lazy">
    <p>This section is written for the Grey we actually place, though the arc is similar for any large parrot, cockatoo included. Teri talks every new owner through four phases so nothing in the first month arrives as a shock:</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Four Adjustment Phases</h3>
    <p>Save this somewhere — it's what separates "my new Grey hates me" from "my Grey is right on track."</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-first-30-days-timeline.webp" srcset="/african-grey-first-30-days-timeline-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-first-30-days-timeline.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Thirty-day adjustment timeline for a new African Grey: settling days one to three, household mapping in week one, trust building in week two, personality stabilizing in weeks three and four" loading="lazy">
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">1</span><b>Days 1–3 · Landing</b><p>Expect a still, watchful bird that perches low and only eats once the room empties. That quiet caution is a healthy Grey finding its feet, not a sad one.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">2</span><b>Week 1 · Learning the House</b><p>Your Grey is mapping the place — who comes and goes, which noises mean what, when meals appear. Hold your routine steady and predictable on purpose.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">3</span><b>Week 2 · Earning Trust</b><p>Now the step-ups turn willing, treats are taken softly from your fingers, and you'll catch the first tentative mimics of sounds from <em>your</em> home.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">4</span><b>Weeks 3–4 · Settling In</b><p>The real personality surfaces, right about when we phone to check in. Every one of our buyers keeps our direct number through that opening month.</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S19 MYTHS -->
  <section id="myths">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">African Grey vs Cockatoo Myths — What's Actually True?</h2>
    <p>Every parrot forum repeats the same confident claims about these two birds, and buyers arrive quoting them. Even solid care guides like <a href="https://www.thesprucepets.com/the-smartest-pet-birds-4178388" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Spruce Pets' smartest-birds overview ↗</a> stick to the verifiable, so here's where the folklore parts ways with real birds.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-myths-reality.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo-myths-reality-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-cockatoo-myths-reality.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Myth versus reality cards debunking claims that African Greys are allergy-safe, that cockatoos are simply cuddly, and that Greys are cold" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Myths We Hear Most</h3>
    <p>A couple of fast ones, then the whopper that earns its own reality check.</p>
    <div class="myth-grid">
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"African Greys are allergy-safe."</strong> They aren't — Greys are powder-down birds, and a peer-reviewed case tied an owner's lung disease to one. Cockatoos are dustier still. Both species need real dander management, not a "clean bird" assumption.</p></div>
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"Cockatoos are just cuddly."</strong> The cuddle is real, but it's inseparable from the screaming, the neediness and the plucking when contact stops. A cockatoo's affection comes with a bill attached, and unprepared owners are the ones who fill the rescues.</p></div>
    </div>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">The Big One: "Greys Are Cold, Cockatoos Are Loving"</h4>
    <p>The most repeated framing online, and the most misleading.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Reality: Two Kinds of Love</h5>
    <p>A Grey bonds as deeply as any cockatoo — it just shows it through attention, conversation and proximity instead of constant physical contact. "Cold" describes a Grey that's under-socialized or newly moved, not the species. And a cockatoo's affection is inseparable from its demands. Neither is warmer; they love on different terms.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: owner reports across both species</h6>
    <p>The pattern matches discussions across the large parrot communities (Reddit's r/parrots, the major Facebook groups): Greys interactive but independent, cockatoos affectionate but demanding — trends real, guarantees nonexistent.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S20 THEY OUTLIVE YOU -->
  <section id="succession">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">They Can Outlive You: Lifespan &amp; Succession Planning</h2>
    <p>Here's the question almost no comparison page asks, and it outweighs talking or noise: <strong>both of these birds can outlive their owners.</strong> An African Grey lives 40–60 years; a large cockatoo can reach 80. A bird bought at 40 may still need care when you're pushing 100.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-cockatoo-lifespan-succession.webp" srcset="/african-grey-cockatoo-lifespan-succession-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-cockatoo-lifespan-succession.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Lifespan timeline showing the African Grey at 40 to 60 years and cockatoos up to 80 years, with a prompt to name a future caretaker" loading="lazy">
    <p>That long life is why rehoming is so common for both species — many large parrots pass through several homes in a lifetime, not from being bad birds but from outlasting jobs, marriages, moves and health. The responsible move either way is a written succession plan: name the person who inherits the bird, make sure they've actually met it, and set aside the paperwork and funds so the handoff isn't a crisis.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">What a Parrot Succession Plan Includes</h3>
    <p>Three things, in writing: a named caretaker who has agreed and spent real time with the bird; the bird's documents — CITES paperwork, health records, band number — in one folder; and a modest fund or instruction covering vet care and food during the transition. It's the same plan whether you choose a Grey or a cockatoo, and doing it is part of buying a decades-long bird responsibly.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-footer-logo-80.webp" width="40" height="40" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S21 CITES -->
  <section id="cites">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">CITES Status &amp; Documentation</h2>
    <img class="sec-img" src="/african-grey-breeder-with-bird-midland-tx.webp" width="760" height="400" alt="C.A.Gs breeder with a documented captive-bred African Grey in Midland, TX" loading="lazy">
    <p>The African Grey holds the treaty's strictest rank, CITES Appendix I — a listing granted in 2017 once wild trapping had gutted native flocks, a backstory <a href="https://www.britannica.com/animal/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Encyclopaedia Britannica ↗</a> lays out well. Several cockatoos, the Moluccan and the Citron's parent species among them, carry Appendix-I or II status of their own. None of it outlaws ownership; what it does is make proof of captive-bred origin the entire game.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">What Paperwork Comes With Every Grey?</h3>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-cites-documentation-flatlay.webp" srcset="/african-grey-cites-documentation-flatlay-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-cites-documentation-flatlay.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" alt="Flat-lay of the C.A.Gs document folder: CITES captive-bred paperwork, hatch certificate with closed band number, DNA sexing certificate and avian vet health certificate" loading="lazy">
    <p>Every Grey leaves with the complete folder: captive-bred CITES papers, a hatch record carrying the closed leg-band number, a DNA sexing certificate and an avian vet's health certificate. Should any seller of any parrot — Grey, cockatoo, whatever — stall when you ask for those four, the stall itself has told you what you need to know.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Appendix I, in Plain English</h4>
    <p>The <a href="https://www.fws.gov/law/wild-bird-conservation-act" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Wild Bird Conservation Act, detailed by the U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service ↗</a>, is the wall that keeps trapped Appendix-I parrots out of American homes. Home-bred birds with documentation move between owners legally. And your Grey's leg band was sealed on in the nest — it can't be forced onto a wild-caught adult later, which is why it outweighs any receipt in the box.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">What IUCN Status Means for Greys and Cockatoos</h5>
    <p>In the wild the Congo Grey is rated Endangered and the Timneh Vulnerable; among the cockatoos here, the Moluccan is Vulnerable and the Citron's parent species Critically Endangered. Your captive-bred bird's legality is untouched by any of that — but it's why we treat documentation as ethics rather than marketing. Each papered, home-bred sale is one fewer market reason to pull a bird from the wild.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: cites.org &amp; IUCN Red List</h6>
    <p>Sources for the listings above: the <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES appendices database ↗</a> and the <a href="https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22724813/154068024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IUCN Red List ↗</a> entries covering <em>Psittacus erithacus</em>, <em>Psittacus timneh</em> and the cockatoos discussed here.</p>
  </section>

